  "prompt": "What is the difference between \"don't we verb\" and \" do we not verb\"?",
  "response": "The phrases \"don't we [verb]\" and \"do we not [verb]\" are both ways to form negative interrogative sentences in English, but they differ in formality, emphasis, and usage context. Here's a breakdown of their differences:\n\n### 1. **Contraction vs. Full Form**\n\n- **Don't we [verb]:**\n  - **Contraction:** \"Don't\" is a contraction of \"do not.\"\n  - **Usage:** More commonly used in spoken and informal contexts.\n  - **Example:** \"Don't we have a meeting today?\"\n\n- **Do we not [verb]:**\n  - **Full Form:** Uses \"do not\" without contraction.\n  - **Usage:** More formal, emphatic, or literary. It can also be used to add emphasis or convey surprise.\n  - **Example:** \"Do we not have a meeting today?\"\n\n### 2. **Formality and Emphasis**\n\n- **Don't we:**\n  - **Less Formal:** Suited for everyday conversations.\n  - **Neutral Emphasis:** Typically used for standard questions without additional emphasis.\n  \n- **Do we not:**\n  - **More Formal or Emphatic:** Often used in formal writing or when the speaker wants to emphasize the negation.\n  - **Greater Emphasis:** Can express stronger doubt, surprise, or insistence.\n  - **Example with Emphasis:** \"Do we not deserve recognition for our hard work?\"\n\n### 3. **Contextual Usage**\n\n- **Don't we:**\n  - **Confirmatory Questions:** Seeking confirmation or agreement.\n  - **Example:** \"Don't we need to submit the report by Friday?\"\n\n- **Do we not:**\n  - **Clarifying or Highlighting a Point:** Pointing out something that the speaker believes should be acknowledged.\n  - **Example:** \"Do we not have the necessary resources to complete this project?\"\n\n### 4. **Regional and Stylistic Preferences**\n\n- **Don't we:** More prevalent in American and British English in everyday dialogue.\n- **Do we not:** Might appear more in written English, formal speeches, or specific stylistic choices.\n\n### Summary\n\nWhile both \"don't we [verb]\" and \"do we not [verb]\" aim to ask negative questions, \"don't we\" is typically used in informal, conversational contexts, whereas \"do we not\" serves in more formal settings or when emphasizing the negation. Choosing between them depends on the desired tone, formality, and the level of emphasis the speaker intends to convey.\n\n---\n\n**Examples:**\n\n1. **Informal/Conversational:**\n   - \"Don't we need to leave now?\"\n\n2. **Formal/Emphatic:**\n   - \"Do we not have the authority to make this decision?\"\n\n3. **Seeking Confirmation:**\n   - \"Don't we agree on this approach?\"\n\n4. **Highlighting a Point:**\n   - \"Do we not owe it to our customers to provide better service?\"\n\n---\n\nUnderstanding these nuances helps in selecting the appropriate form based on the context and the message you wish to convey.",
